  "prompt": "When do the rabies symptoms occur in humans?",
  "response": "Rabies symptoms in humans typically appear after an incubation period of about 1 to 3 months following exposure to the virus, although this can vary widely from as little as a few days to several years in rare cases. The timing of symptom onset depends on several factors, including the location of the bite, the severity of the wound, the amount of virus introduced into the body, and the individual\u2019s immune response.\n\nThe initial symptoms of rabies may be quite non-specific and can include fever, headache, and general malaise. As the disease progresses, more specific neurological symptoms can develop, such as confusion, agitation, hallucinations, hydrophobia (fear of water), paralysis, and ultimately, coma and death if left untreated. Once symptoms appear, rabies is almost universally fatal, so prompt medical attention and post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) after exposure to a potentially rabid animal are critical.",
